segments.text: When I was there, one of the first things I was asked to do was look at the regulations in regard to their agreement with federal regulations.
And I took one look at it and I said, hey guys, we're in violation.
And they said, well, what do you recommend we do?
And I said, I recommend one of two things.
One is you can initiate procedures which will probably trigger the review they told us that they were ultimately going to get around to.

and they'll say we have to change it or two you can go downstairs and tell the city council and their attitude is the hell with it or three you can ignore it well we ignored it for about six months to eight months and the review finally got around and they told us that if we did not modify our ordinances to conform they are going to uh no this is a fia flip insurance administration but
that if we did not perform, they would suspend all FDIC institutions from loaning any money for development and purchases of property inside the city of Galveston.
Well, you know, that kind of excites everybody because there's lots of money there.
And the outcome was we finally got an ordinance adopted after a lot of screaming and yelling.

I had a very good ordinance drafted, but it was too long and complex for the politicals to put up with, so they threw it out and adopted a short four-page type ordinance that was much more restrictive.

Now, the reason it was was because politically it looked better to have a short four-page typed ordinance that people could read and understand instead of having one that was much more specific about what you could do if you could do the following things to protect the system, which got to be about 25, 30 pages long.
specifying wiring, ventilation systems, and all kinds of things.
So the outcome was they adopted that ordinance and they had periodically given exemptions, which are complete violations of the federal regs, to industrial and commercial facilities.
I'm going to have to run it a little bit.
Right.
How would you characterize the planning style at Galveston as, for example, would it be considered basically kind of oriented toward a general comprehensive plan, sort of synoptic?

concept of planning, a holistic approach, or would it be incremental planning, opportunism, would it be advocacy planning, would it be radical planning, structural changes in government, for example, caused by any...
I think in general what I saw in Galveston was that
there was too much weight there to try certain things.
There was a very real sense of pragmatism.
Can we get this done?
Can we get it through?
Should we spend time on it at this stage?
There was a lot of advocacy planning that was going on and that would get hot and people would stop being advocates and become bureaucrats or technocrats again for a while.
There was a lot of arm twisting, political interaction.
There was, I think, some commitment to comprehensive planning, and the plan was being basically used as the document from which a lot of these proposals for action would occur.
You know, street closures, park development, linear parks,
In other words, the plan became kind of a basis of ideas for which practical advocate kinds of activities occurred.
I think there was that commitment.
Now, on the other hand, you kind of look at it and there were some things that happened that maybe didn't relate that closely to the plan, but I think there was

general consensus that okay the plan is in many cases abstract or vague enough we don't understand what that means but here's an opportunity let's grab it and federal money was viewed as an opportunity and we'll take it we'll find a way to make it fit within the community and the plan very good kevin thank you very much for all of your help on this and if we have any follow-up
